               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18301209-226-person1925">
                  JOHN 
                  TOWNSEND
               <interp inst="t18301209-226-person1925" type="surname" value="TOWNSEND"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18301209-226-person1925" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18301209-226-person1925" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I live in <placeName id="t18301209-226-crimeloc1265">Goswell-street</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18301209-226-crimeloc1265" type="placeName" value="Goswell-street"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18301209-226-crimeloc1265" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18301209-226-off1263 t18301209-226-crimeloc1265"></join>, and am a paper-stainer. I know the prisoner, he was in the employ of Mr. George Hughes; I have purchased wine of him, and the prisoner delivered part of it on the 2nd of August - he came to my house, and said he was sent by Mr. Hughes for empty bottles, and I delivered him five dozen, for which he gave me this receipt; they were due to Mr. Hughes, and I gave them to the prisoner as his <rs id="t18301209-226-deflabel1266" type="occupation">servant</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18301209-226-defend1922 t18301209-226-deflabel1266"></join> - Mr. Hughes had charged me for the bottles, and the charge was to be taken off when they were returned: (receipt read.)</p>
               <p>2nd of August, 1830. Returned five dozen empty bottles for G. Hughes. - J. NEALER.</p>

               <p>GEORGE HUGHES. I am a <rs id="t18301209-226-viclabel1267" type="occupation">wine-merchant</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18301209-226-victim1924 t18301209-226-viclabel1267"></join>, and live in Goswell-road. The Prisoner was in my service till July;<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183012090107"></xptr>I expected to receive these bottles from Mr. Townsend: I had charged him with them, and upon their reaching me, I should have given him credit for them; they were worth 15s.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18301209-226-person1926">
                  JOHN 
                  SMITH
               <interp inst="t18301209-226-person1926" type="surname" value="SMITH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18301209-226-person1926" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18301209-226-person1926" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a Police-constable. I took the prisoner; I did not make him any promise or threat, but he said he had not taken more than twenty dozen, and he had done it to support his father.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. On the 23rd of August, Mr. Hughes' son said to me, "James, we are very short of bottles, do you know where there are any owing;" I said Yes, at Mr. Townsend's - he said, "Go and fetch them;" I went, and got them - I did not see my master; he was denied, as he was afraid of being arrested for debt - I gave the bottles to his son; and said he had better put them down - he said, "I shall not; come in and have a game at marbles."</p>
               <p>MR. HUGHES. He had left me on the 2nd of August.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18301209-226-verdict1268" type="verdictDescription">
